chunk_content: • Identify programmatic gaps by analyzing the number and ages of people receiving services, as well as the reach of services in particular geographic areas. How to collect: Data sources are standard program monitoring tools, such as forms, logbooks, spreadsheets, and databases that national programs and/or partners develop or already use. Data should be collected continuously at the point of service delivery (i.e., ANC, PMTCT, ART, etc.) and aggregated in time for PEPFAR reporting cycles. The indicator can be generated by counting the number of persons receiving post-GBV clinical care, disaggregated by the age group and sex of the client receiving the service, as well as the type of service (sexual violence or emotional/physical violence) and PEP provision (see below for disaggregation information). To adequately capture the provision of these services, logs and monitoring forms will need to be used wherever the services are offered.
